Fit a logistic regression model with PCA-based features¶

Compare the preprocessing steps and model fitting results to the elastic net model from last week. The PCA based features are used in logistic regression without a penalty, and logistic regression with the lasso (l1-norm) penalty. We will use the Sonar data set as last week.

After tuning both models, tree-based methods are quickly introduced to demonstrate models that do not require as much preprocessing steps.

How many PCs should we use?¶

The fraction of the variance explained for each PC.

In [32]:
fraction_var_explain = pca_object.explained_variance_ratio_
In [33]:
pc_numbers = np.arange(len(fraction_var_explain)) + 1

Create the "scree plot" to visualize the fraction of the variance explained for each PC.

In [34]:
sns.set_style('whitegrid')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))

ax.plot(pc_numbers, fraction_var_explain, 'bo-')

ax.set_xlabel('PC')
ax.set_ylabel('Variance explained ratio')

plt.show()

Another approach is to consider the cumulative variance explained, rather than the fraction per PC.

In [35]:
total_var_explain = fraction_var_explain.cumsum()
In [36]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))

ax.plot(pc_numbers, total_var_explain, 'bo-')

ax.axhline(y=0.5, color='grey', linestyle='--')

ax.axhline(y=0.8, color='black', linestyle='--')

ax.axhline(y=0.95, color = 'red', linestyle='--')

ax.set_xlabel('PC')
ax.set_ylabel('Total variance explained')

plt.show()

PCA as a preprocessing step¶

PCA is sometimes referred as a feature extraction method when we have many correlated input features to a predictive model. We do not know how many PCs to retain. The approaches we discussed above are when we are not focused on predicting a response. When using PCA as a pre-processing step to extract features, we should tune the number of PCs with cross-validation.

We need to correctly executed within each cross-validation fold. We must first standardize, then perform PCA, extract the desired number of PCs, finally use those PCs as input features to a model. This is known as PC-regression (when predicting continuous responses), PC-based logistic regression (for binary responses). The PCs can even be used as input features to neural networks! This is known as neural networks with feature extraction.

We will use the Pipeline to appropriately apply the preprocessing steps before fitting the model.

Create the pipeline¶

Use logistic regression without a penalty term. Initialize model objects.

In [37]:
standardize_features = StandardScaler()

pca_to_fit = PCA()

logistic_mle = LogisticRegression(penalty='none', max_iter=10001, solver='lbfgs')

Define the pipeline.

In [38]:
pca_logistic_workflow = Pipeline( steps= [ ('std_scale', standardize_features),
                                         ('pca', pca_to_fit),
                                         ('logistic', logistic_mle)])

We will tune the number of PCs to retain. Remember the Pipeline syntax requirements:

<step>__<parameter>

In [39]:
### the tuning grid is a dictionary

pca_tune_grid = {'pca__n_components': [5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30]}

Define the cross-validation¶

In [40]:
my_cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, n_repeats=3, random_state=101)

Define the NumPy feature arrays¶

Ensemble of trees¶

Fit hundreds of decision trees to slight variations of the training set. Average across those trees. This known as the bagged tree. And if we randomly select the number of features to consider when making a split in the tree, that's known as the random forest.

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.html

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.html

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
